#include <hexi/allocators/block_allocator.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <iostream>

template<size_t element_count = 10>
void demonstrate_block_allocator_behavior() {
    // Create block_allocator with a small number of elements (for demonstration)
    hexi::block_allocator<uint8_t, element_count> allocator;

    std::cout << "=== Block Allocator Free List Management Demonstration ===\n";
    std::cout << "Allocator created with " << element_count << " elements\n";

    // Initial state: all blocks are in free list (pushed during initialization)
    std::cout << "\nStep 1: Initial allocation - blocks are added to free list via constructor\n";

    // Allocate blocks - this internally calls pop() to remove from free list
    uint8_t* block1 = allocator.allocate();
    std::cout << "Allocated block1 - pop() removed it from free list\n";

    uint8_t* block2 = allocator.allocate();
    std::cout << "Allocated block2 - pop() removed it from free list\n";

    // Demonstrate deallocation - this internally calls push() to add back to free list
    std::cout << "\nStep 2: Deallocation - blocks are returned to free list via push()\n";
    allocator.deallocate(block1);
    std::cout << "Deallocated block1 - push() added it back to free list\n";

    // Allocate again - should get the previously deallocated block first
    std::cout << "\nStep 3: Subsequent allocation - gets from free list via pop()\n";
    uint8_t* block3 = allocator.allocate();
    std::cout << "Allocated block3 - pop() retrieved it from free list\n";

    // Verify the behavior
    std::cout << "\n=== Verification ===\n";
    std::cout << "When we deallocate a block, it's pushed to the head of the free list\n";
    std::cout << "Subsequent allocations pop from the head, giving priority to recently freed blocks\n";
    std::cout << "This demonstrates the LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) nature of the free list management\n";

    // Cleanup remaining allocations
    allocator.deallocate(block2);
    allocator.deallocate(block3);
}

// Example usage:
// demonstrate_block_allocator_behavior<3>(); // Use 3 elements for demonstration
```

**Explanation:**

This implementation demonstrates the free list management by:

1. **Constructor Behavior**: Shows how `initialise_free_list()` sets up the initial free list by pushing all blocks onto the list
2. **Allocation (`allocate()`)**: Demonstrates how `pop()` removes blocks from the free list when allocations occur
3. **Deallocation (`deallocate()`)**: Shows how `push()` adds blocks back to the free list when they're freed
4. **LIFO Pattern**: Illustrates the Last-In-First-Out behavior where recently deallocated blocks are prioritized in subsequent allocations

The comments explain the internal operations, showing how `push()` and `pop()` manage the free list even though they're private methods. The demonstration uses a small number of elements to clearly show the allocation/deallocation sequence.

